job.title: Get paid for using AI-based coding assistant to help you with your regular work
job.description:
We're looking for developers with 6 months+ experience to try out using a new code assistant as part of your work in Visual Studio Code. This is an opportunity to continue whatever programming work you already do full-time, while getting extra compensation by trying our code assistant as part of it.

The assistant only works in VSCode, so you must plan to do your programming work in that app. You can be programming in any language/using any stack.

You'll work with a cutting edge code assistant made by a company founded by folks who have built leading AI/Machine Learning safety agendas. The new tool that you'll try has some similarity to other new technologies like Github's Copilot (https://copilot.github.com/) and Replit + Codex (https://blog.replit.com/codex).

We're looking for multiple programmers who can integrate this into their existing work; we don’t have any coding tasks we’d like you to do, other than using the assistant. That said, your interactions will go to our database, so this shouldn’t be used while working on anything confidential.

We plan to pay based on the number of times you use the assistant, with a goal of reaching an average hourly rate that makes sense for both of us.

occupation.scopeNote: Full stack development involves both the front and back-end of a website or application.

ontologySkill.scopeNote: Python is a general-purpose, high-level programming language whose design philosophy emphasizes code readability. Python claims to combine "remarkable power with very clear syntax", and its standard library is large and comprehensive.

C++ (pronounced "cee plus plus") is a statically typed, free-form, multi-paradigm, compiled, general-purpose programming language. It is regarded as an intermediate-level language, as it comprises a combination of both high-level and low-level language features.

Ruby is a dynamic, reflective, general-purpose object-oriented programming language that combines syntax inspired by Perl with Smalltalk-like features. It was also influenced by Eiffel and Lisp. Ruby was first designed and developed in the mid-1990s by Yukihiro "Matz" Matsumoto in Japan.
Structured Query Language (SQL) is a programming language designed for managing data in relational database management systems (RDBMS).

JavaScript is a prototype-based scripting language that is dynamic, weakly typed and has first-class functions. It is a multi-paradigm language, supporting object-oriented, imperative, and functional programming styles.
